  "eprint": {
    "title": "Provably Secure Masking of AES",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Johannes Blömer",
        "email": "krummel@uni-paderborn",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Jorge Guajardo Merchan",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Volker Krummel",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "A general method to\nsecure cryptographic algorithm implementations against side-channel\nattacks is the use of randomization techniques and, in particular,\nmasking. Roughly speaking, using random values unknown to an adversary\none masks the input to a cryptographic algorithm.  As a result, the\nintermediate results in the algorithm computation are uncorrelated to\nthe input and the adversary cannot obtain any useful information from\nthe side-channel. Unfortunately, previous AES randomization techniques\nhave based their security on heuristics and experiments. Thus, flaws\nhave been found which make AES randomized implementations still\nvulnerable to side-channel cryptanalysis.  In this paper, we provide a\nformal notion of security for randomized maskings of arbitrary\ncryptographic algorithms.\nFurthermore, we present an AES randomization technique\nthat is provably secure against side-channel attacks if the adversary\nis able to access a single intermediate result. Our randomized masking technique is quite general\nand it can be applied to arbitrary algorithms using only arithmetic\noperations over some even characteristic finite field.  We notice\nthat to our knowledge this is the first time that a randomization\ntechnique for the AES has been proven secure in a formal model.",
    "keywords": [
      "AES",
      "side-channel attacks",
      "provable secure countermeasures",
      "DPA",
      "hardware implementation",
      "security model"
    ],
